Docker for High-Performance Computing 芒聙聰 Containerized MPI Workloads
Objectives
Design and deploy a multi-container MPI cluster using Docker and Docker Compose, with SSH-based inter-node communication
Implement and benchmark a distributed parallel computation that demonstrates measurable speedup across multiple MPI processes
Build a production-ready, cloud-deployable HPC container image with health checks, resource constraints, and auto-scaling logic
Prerequisites
Comfort with Linux command-line operations including file editing, process management, and network diagnostics
Conceptual understanding of parallel computing: what MPI (Message Passing Interface) is, what ranks and communicators mean, and why distributed workloads require inter-process communication
Lab Environment
You will work on a dedicated AWS EC2 Ubuntu instance provided by Al Nafi. The instance has a base Ubuntu installation; you will install all required tools in Task 1.

Task 1: Install and Verify the HPC Toolchain
Step 1.1 芒聙聰 Install Docker Engine, Docker Compose, and MPI development libraries
Install Docker Engine from the official Docker apt repository, then install OpenMPI and its development headers, Python 3 with pip, and the mpi4py and numpy Python packages. After installation, add your current user to the docker group so subsequent commands do not require sudo, then apply the group change to your current shell session.

Official Docker installation guide (use this if any URL below has changed): https://docs.docker.com/engine/install/ubuntu/

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y ca-certificates curl gnupg lsb-release

sudo install -m 0755 -d /etc/apt/keyrings
curl -fsSL https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu/gpg \
  | sudo gpg --dearmor -o /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg
sudo chmod a+r /etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg

printf 'deb [arch=%s signed-by=/etc/apt/keyrings/docker.gpg] https://download.docker.com/linux/ubuntu %s stable\n' \
  "$(dpkg --print-architecture)" \
  "$(lsb_release -cs)" \
  | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/docker.list

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y docker-ce docker-ce-cli containerd.io docker-compose-plugin

sudo usermod -aG docker "$USER"
newgrp docker
